Splitting 'apple,banana,cherry,dogfood' with a comma as the splitting point  returns a list of two items: the first is the text 'apple' and the second is the text  'banana,cherry,dogfood'.  Notice that the comma after 'apple' does not appear in the result,  because that is the dividing point.

Splitting 'one,two,three,four' at ',' (comma) returns the list '(one two three four)'.  Splitting 'one-potato,two-potato,three-potato,four' at '-potato', returns the list '(one two three four)'.
LANG_TEXT_SPLIT_TOOLTIP_SPLIT_AT_ANY: Divides the given text into a list, using any of the items in the list 'at' as the  dividing point, and returns a list of the results.
